my main reference for constant character and loops and other more complex pipelines are comfyui workflows, which seem a bit complicated. advice for setting these up as generators/pipelines









Use ComfyUI workflows as reference implementations, not UI models.

Best rule:

comfy workflow = internal graph
beast generator = human-facing tool

how to convert Comfy → Beast

1. Find the stable spine

input → identity lock → pose/motion control → sampler/render → postprocess → output

2. Hide plumbing
    Do not expose every Comfy node. Most nodes are implementation detail.
3. Expose only meaningful controls
    For constant character / loops, likely:

character reference
character descriptor
motion template
camera/framing
style
duration
seed
quality/speed mode

4. Turn node clusters into sections
    Example:

$group: character
$section: identity
$group: motion
$section: loop
$group: render
$section: model
$group: export
$section: ffmpeg

5. Ship presets first
    Do not start with arbitrary workflow building.

Start with 3 strong generators:

character-idle-loop
character-walk-loop
character-pacing-stage

6. Keep "advanced" collapsed
    Expose details only when needed:

advanced sampler
advanced controlnet
advanced ffmpeg

Beast version

comfy = graph complexity
beast = generator simplicity

A Beast generator should feel like:

pick character
pick motion
pick style
generate

while internally it may run 30 Comfy-like steps.

key warning

Do not make Beast into "Comfy but vertical."

Make Beast:

opinionated generators
with editable CDI underneath

That gives power without drowning users.








